{"abstract":[{"text":"Defining Emacs Lisp functions directly from Swift.","type":"text"}],"schemaVersion":{"major":0,"patch":0,"minor":3},"primaryContentSections":[{"kind":"content","content":[{"text":"defun","type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"defun"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/Environment"},{"text":" provides many overloads of the ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"defun"},{"text":" method allowing you to convert Swift functions to Lisp functions.","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"All the variants take 3 arguments:"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"optional name for a new function ("},{"code":"nil","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" for lambda)"}]}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"docstring (empty by default)"}]}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"function implementation as a Swift closure"}],"type":"paragraph"}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"It returns an opaque ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/EmacsValue","type":"reference","isActive":true},{"text":" that can be called via ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"funcall"},{"type":"text","text":" or "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"apply"},{"text":" (mostly useful for lambda functions).","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"If something goes wrong on the Emacs side, it can throw ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/EmacsError"},{"text":", however, it is much less likely compared to calls.","type":"text"}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Let’s start with this simple example to see how it works:"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"syntax":"swift","code":["env.defun(\"swift-+\") { (lhs: Int, rhs: Int) -> Int in lhs + rhs }"],"type":"codeListing"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"This will define a Lisp function named "},{"code":"swift-+","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" taking exactly two arguments. You can call it like any other Lisp function."}]},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"emacs-lisp","code":["(swift-+ 1 1) ;; => 2"]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"If you pass not integers as arguments, you get "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"wrong-type-argument"},{"text":" like with any other Lisp function expecting certain types from its arguments.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"You can use any type that is convertible to Lisp (see "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/TypeConversions","type":"reference","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":") as your closure argument\/return types to get this sweet automatic conversion."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"level":2,"text":"Acquiring the Environment","type":"heading","anchor":"Acquiring-the-Environment"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Our "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"swift-+"},{"text":" function is nice, but we don’t communicate with Emacs internals in it, while in the majority of cases we’d want to call a thing or two from the Lisp side. Since our code is a closure, we might have a temptation to simply capture the ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/Environment","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"type":"text","text":" variable and use it. DON’T DO THAT. See more on the reasons in "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/Lifetimes","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"type":"text","text":", but for now just remember to add it as a parameter into your closure."}]},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["env.defun(\"swift-+\") {","  (env: Environment, lhs: Int, rhs: Int) throws -> Int in","  try env.funcall(\"+\", with: lhs, rhs)","}"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"This new version still can be called exactly the same way, but now it calls a Lisp function itself."}]},{"style":"important","type":"aside","name":"Important","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Don’t capture environment in your function’s body. If you need it, add it as a first parameter of your closure."}]}]},{"anchor":"Using-Opaque-Values","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Using Opaque Values"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Sometimes we don’t want to use a fancy conversion in our function and we simply want to forward our dynamically typed argument to another Lisp function. This is totally valid and we can use ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/EmacsValue","isActive":true},{"text":" directly in our function’s signature.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["env.defun(\"to-string\") {","  (env: Environment, value: EmacsValue) throws -> String in","  try env.funcall(\"format\", with: \"%S\", value)","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"This function takes an opaque value and forwards it to another function. We re-throw any exceptions coming from that call, so if that function has some type expectation for it’s argument, the user still gets notified about it."}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Opaque values have very specific lifetime rules to them. Please, check "},{"isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/Lifetimes","type":"reference"},{"text":" for more detail.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}],"style":"important","type":"aside","name":"Important"}]}],"variants":[{"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}],"paths":["\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/defininglispfunctions"]}],"identifier":{"url":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/DefiningLispFunctions","interfaceLanguage":"swift"},"sections":[],"kind":"article","seeAlsoSections":[{"title":"Getting started","generated":true,"identifiers":["doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/DefiningAModule","doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/CallingLispFunctions","doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/TypeConversions","doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/ErrorHandling"]}],"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule"],["doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule","doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/Environment"]]},"metadata":{"role":"article","modules":[{"name":"EmacsSwiftModule"}],"title":"Defining Lisp Functions","roleHeading":"Article"},"references":{"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule":{"role":"collection","kind":"symbol","url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule","identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"A Swift library to write Emacs plugins in Swift!"}],"title":"EmacsSwiftModule","type":"topic"},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/Environment":{"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Environment is the interaction point with Emacs. If you want to do anything on the Emacs side, you need to have an Environment."}],"title":"Environment","fragments":[{"text":"class","kind":"keyword"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"text":"Environment","kind":"identifier"}],"navigatorTitle":[{"text":"Environment","kind":"identifier"}],"role":"symbol","kind":"symbol","identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/Environment","type":"topic","url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/environment"},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/TypeConversions":{"url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/typeconversions","type":"topic","title":"Type conversions","identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/TypeConversions","kind":"article","role":"article","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Converting Swift values into Lisp values and vice versa."}]},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/EmacsError":{"url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/emacserror","abstract":[{"text":"The main type representing Emacs errors.","type":"text"}],"fragments":[{"text":"enum","kind":"keyword"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"text":"EmacsError","kind":"identifier"}],"title":"EmacsError","navigatorTitle":[{"kind":"identifier","text":"EmacsError"}],"kind":"symbol","identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/EmacsError","role":"symbol","type":"topic"},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/Lifetimes":{"abstract":[{"text":"Emacs internals lifetimes.","type":"text"}],"url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/lifetimes","title":"Lifetimes","kind":"article","identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/Lifetimes","role":"article","type":"topic"},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/ErrorHandling":{"url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/errorhandling","type":"topic","title":"Error Handling","identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/ErrorHandling","kind":"article","role":"article","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Handling Lisp errors on Swift side and vice versa."}]},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/DefiningAModule":{"url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/definingamodule","type":"topic","title":"Defining a module","identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/DefiningAModule","kind":"article","role":"article","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Defining a new Emacs module from Swift."}]},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/EmacsValue":{"abstract":[{"text":"An opaque Emacs value representing something from the Emacs Lisp world.","type":"text"}],"url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/emacsvalue","fragments":[{"text":"class","kind":"keyword"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"kind":"identifier","text":"EmacsValue"}],"title":"EmacsValue","navigatorTitle":[{"text":"EmacsValue","kind":"identifier"}],"kind":"symbol","identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/EmacsValue","role":"symbol","type":"topic"},"doc://EmacsSwiftModule/documentation/EmacsSwiftModule/CallingLispFunctions":{"url":"\/documentation\/emacsswiftmodule\/callinglispfunctions","type":"topic","title":"Calling Lisp Functions","identifier":"doc:\/\/EmacsSwiftModule\/documentation\/EmacsSwiftModule\/CallingLispFunctions","kind":"article","role":"article","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Calling Lisp functions from your Swift code."}]}}}